"{\"uid\": \"thesouthafrican.com-sport-paris-olympics-2024-olympic-games-latest-day-two-update-from-paris\", \"text\": \"Copyright Blue Sky Publications (Pty) Ltd. All Rights Reserved.  thesouthafrican.com is a division of Blue Sky Publications Ltd. Reproduction without permission prohibited  Home\\u00bbSport\\u00bbParis Olympics 2024\\u00bbOlympic games latest: Day two update from Paris  Get your latest update on the progress of South African athletes on day two of the Games of the XXXIII Olympiad in Paris.  Team South Africa's Olympic efforts are in full swing at Paris 2024 as the action continues on day two of the Olympiad.  Individual and team efforts have already proudly represented South Africa at the games on Saturday.  In men's hockey South Africa found themselves up against it early on after giving up a penalty flick that gave world No 1 Netherlands the lead. While they would level the scores with a spectacular first goal of the tournament. However with player's short, South Africa struggled to contain the Dutch who raced out to 4-1 lead. While the green and gold fought back valiantly they could not do enough to avoid a 5-3 opening match defeat.  Judoka Geronay Whitebooi made it through the round of 32 with an emphatic victory over Jacqueline Solis of Argentina but she would come unstuck in the Round of 16 against Natsumi Tsunoda of Japan.  Paige Badenhorst finished third in her heat in 7:39.19 to qualify for the quarter-finals of the Women's single scull rowing event.  Meanwhile in the poolErin Gallagherfinished sixth in her heat in 57.80 to qualify 13th fastest for the evening semi-finals in the 100 metre butterfly. China's Yufei Zhang was quickest in 56.50sec.  HOCKEY  Men's Pool A: RESULTTeam SA 3 Netherlands 5  JUDO  Women's -48kg elimination, round of 32: WIN!Geronay Whitebooi, ranked No39 in the world, beat her opponent Jacqueline Solis of Argentina 10-1 (ippon). The end came at 3:57 into the contest  Women's -48kg elimination, round of 16: RESULTGeronay Whitebooi lost to Natsumi Tsunoda (Japan)  ROWING  Women's single scull, heats: THROUGH!Paige Badenhorst finished third in her heat in 7:39.19 to qualify for the quarter-finals  SWIMMING  Women's 100m butterfly, heats: THROUGH!Erin Gallagher finished sixth in her heat in 57.80 to qualify 13th fastest for the evening semi-finals. China's Yufei Zhang was quickest in 56.50sec.  BADMINTON  Women's singles, Group H (2.50pm):Johanita Scholtz vs Kim-Ga Eun (Kor)Note:Scholtz is ranked No43 in the world and Eun is ranked No13  EQUESTRIAN  Eventing, Individual dressage (In progress):Alexander Peternell  RUGBY SEVENS  Men's semi-final (3.30pm):Team SA vs FranceTheMen's bronze (7pm):TBCMen's final (7.45pm):TBC  SURFING  Men's first round, heats (from 7pm):Jordy Smith and Matt McGillivrayWomen's first round, heats (from 11.48pm):Sarah Baum  SWIMMINGWomen's 100m butterfly, semi-finals (8.30pm):Erin Gallagher  SKATEBOARDING  (Postponed until Monday due to weather)  Men's street prelims:Brandon ValjaloMen's street final:Brandon Valjalo TBC  Let us know by clicking on the comment tab below this article or by emailinginfo@thesouthafrican.comor sending a WhatsApp to 060 011 021 1.  You can also follow@TheSAnews on XandThe South African on Facebookfor the latest news.  WIN R2 000: Take The South African's SASSA Survey  The South African is hiring! Freelance writing positions available  Follow The South African on Facebook for the latest local and international news  Follow The South African's WhatsApp channel for the latest sport, lifestyle and local news  Follow The South African on X for the latest, breaking news  A brand new shopping mall is coming to Pretoria East, bringing major retailers and new convenience to the area.  Orlando Pirates are reportedly set to welcome a new staff member in former Stellenbosch FC Head of Recruitment Brendon Fourie.  Masindi Nemtajela was stretched off during Orlando Pirates' 6-0 win over TS Galaxy on Sunday afternoon in Mbombela.  IT support is not just technical, it is personal.  Liema Pantsi's victory was clouded as fans of the 'Big Brother Mzansi' show expressed that Smash Afrika was unprofessional towards her.  A dominant weekend for the SA teams in the URC has made a big impact on the latest log standings as the playoffs edge closer.    TheSouthAfrican.com is all about South Africa and the stories that affect South Africans, wherever they are in the world.  We are independent.No agenda.No bias.  Our offices are for administrative purposes only, no visitors will be accepted without an appointment.  South Africa- Blue Sky Publications (Pty) Ltd - Registration Number: 2005/028472/07 - Address: Regus Business Centre, 1st Floor, Block B, North Park, Black River Park, 2 Fir Street, Observatory, Cape Town, 7925, South Africa  Copyright Blue Sky Publications (Pty) Ltd. All Rights Reserved.\"}"